If the weather cooperates, I'll be flying again on Saturday.
I also found a pink logbook.
Happy Saturday morning. That's what I did today ^_^
#TeaganAir
It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe what it's like to fly a small airplane, I would say it's a mix of a motorcycle/quad and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're very fast immediately. It's all somewhat unstable on the ground, that's why motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know it yet: You steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the throttle. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's wobbly and you kind of float. It feels like you're in a boat on the water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you off course, so you have to get used to the sea motion, just up in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs hurt, as if I had been to the gym.
This is not like a Sunday drive in the car. It's more of a sport than a leisurely ride, in my newly gained opinion.
It's a beautiful Saturday, my loved ones. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
I'll be back tomorrow. Then we'll practice stalls and slow flight.
Today the weather was unstable, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. At one point, we had a ground speed of only 16 mph and an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit hazy higher up, but still beautiful.
